{"key":"post-10327004","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>10327004</id>\n<content>Mushrooms are not something you can grow hydroponically and do not benefit from 'nutrients in the water'.&amp;nbsp; Everyone who has tried some sort of wicking method to water their substrates has found it stalls fruiting and waterlogs the substrate.&amp;nbsp; Moisture LEAVING a substrate is a major pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; You let a substrate dry during the flush, and then after the flush, you flood it with water to hydrate it for the next flush, when the drying process is repeated.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You have to remember, mycelium is not a plant and does not benefit from techniques that plants benefit from.&amp;nbsp; In fact, fungi is more closely related to mammals than to plants.&amp;nbsp; One of the hardest things for new mushroom growers, especially those who have grown plants/gardens, is to unlearn just about every thing they've ever learned about horticulture in order to be successful at mycology.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>10327393</next>\n<prev>10326795</prev>\n<first>10325740</first>\n<last>10327975</last>\n<when>1242152580</when>\n<utime>05/12/09 09:23 PM</utime>\n</post>"}